Odd-level SU(2) orbit tropical obstruction search
Date: 2026-07-22 UTC

Build
-----
$ make -B -j1 search_su2_odd_orbit_tropical
g++ -O2 -std=c++20 -Wall -Wextra -Wpedantic -Wconversion \
    -Wsign-conversion -Wshadow -Werror \
    search_su2_odd_orbit_tropical.cpp \
    -o search_su2_odd_orbit_tropical

Deterministic search
--------------------
$ /usr/bin/time -f 'elapsed=%e maxrss=%MKB' \
    ./search_su2_odd_orbit_tropical 15 1000000 50
progress rank=5 level=9 trials=1000000 result=PASS
progress rank=6 level=11 trials=1000000 result=PASS
progress rank=7 level=13 trials=1000000 result=PASS
progress rank=8 level=15 trials=1000000 result=PASS
progress rank=9 level=17 trials=1000000 result=PASS
progress rank=10 level=19 trials=1000000 result=PASS
progress rank=11 level=21 trials=1000000 result=PASS
progress rank=12 level=23 trials=1000000 result=PASS
progress rank=13 level=25 trials=1000000 result=PASS
progress rank=14 level=27 trials=1000000 result=PASS
progress rank=15 level=29 trials=1000000 result=PASS
SU2_ODD_ORBIT_TROPICAL ranks=5..15 trials_per_rank=1000000 \
    maximum_direction=50 result=PASS
elapsed=254.60 maxrss=2560KB

For every trial, the generator support, signs, minimum exponent parities,
and extra even-exponent direction are generated by a fixed xorshift seed.
The program evaluates the logarithmic squared-base functional on every
unordered spectral pair.  A unique negative maximizer would be an eventual
high-power counterexample along that direction and causes immediate FAIL.

PASS is a bounded obstruction search, not a proof of GKS2*.  It does not
exhaust supports or directions and does not certify convex transport when
several spectral pairs share the asymptotic boundary.
